@phdthesis{Slingerland2000,
abstract = {Reconsidering 40 years of research and development activity aiming at crop-livestock integration in the West African savanna, shows that the suggested model of crop-livestock integration contains at least three major flaws: it neglects the farm context, the financing role of livestock, and competition for land and labour. This thesis addresses these flaws in the context of a rapidly growing population. Zoundw{\'{e}}go province in Burkina Faso, and the village of Ka{\"{i}}bo Sud V5 in particular, serve as the study area and generate examples for the relevant issues. Additional data were collected in Sanmatenga province and in Ziro province. In the development perspective of mixed farming, farming systems were ranged from separate specialized low external input systems to specialized high external inputs systems. For the Mossi, wealth is the drive towards mixed farming, and for the Fulani poverty. Sales of livestock for financing purposes negatively affect livestock production through foregone offspring and liveweight, and limit crop production through foregone manure and animal traction. Current high population growth leads to an expanded area under crops and consequently reduced grazing area in the rainy season. Mossi respond by increasing their control over scarce feed resources, especially when they become mixed farmers owning cattle, excluding Fulani from their village territories. The study concludes that societal demands dictate the need for a variety of farming types. It is thus recommended to abandon the rather rigid mixed farming model and to focus on the consequences of the principles underlying crop-livestock integration in development efforts.},
